[[image:bertrandserletPR.jpg|thumb|180px|Bertrand Serlet]]
'''Bertrand Serlet''' is senior vice president of [[software engineering]] at [[Apple Inc.]]<ref name="applebio">{{cite web | url=http://www.apple.com/pr/bios/serlet.html | title=Apple - Press Info - Bios - Bertrand Serlet | publisher=Apple Computer | year=July 2003 | accessdate=2006-09-16}}</ref>.  He succeeded [[Avie Tevanian]] to the position in July 2003<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.apple.com/pr/library/2003/jul/08avie.html | title=Avie Tevanian Named Chief Software Technology Officer of Apple | year=July 8, 2003 | publisher=Apple Computer | accessdate=2006-09-16}}</ref>. In this position he has been primarily responsible for the release of the 10.4 versions of [[Mac OS X]] and [[Mac OS X Server]] and the upcoming 10.5 versions<ref>{{cite web | url=http://daringfireball.net/2006/03/adios_avie | title=Adios Avie | author=John Gruber | year=March 31, 2006 | work=Daring Fireball | accessdate=2006-09-16}}</ref>. 

Before Apple he worked at [[Xerox]]<ref name="applebio"/>, and [[NeXT]]<ref name="applebio"/>.

He recently spoke at [[WWDC]] 2006, on the similarities between Mac OS X Tiger and Windows Vista, including the comparison of Apple [[Mac OS X]] Aqua interface, and Microsoft Vista's Aero interface.

